()` can fail with `BindFailed` and advertising can fail independently.\n**Status:** Compliant\n\n---\n\n### [INFO] DiscoveryEvent Enum\n**Spec reference:** Plan, Chunk 1 item 3\n**Finding:** `DiscoveryEvent` has exactly `PeerDiscovered(RawDiscoveredPeer)`, `PeerUpdated(RawDiscoveredPeer)`, `PeerLost(String)` as specified.\n**Status:** Compliant\n\n---\n\n### [INFO] RawDiscoveredPeer and AdvertisementSpec\n**Spec reference:** Plan, Chunk 1 item 4\n**Finding:** Both types are defined in `types.rs`. `RawDiscoveredPeer` includes `instance_name`, `addresses: Vec<IpAddr>`, `port`, `txt_records: HashMap<String, String>`, and `discovered_at: Instant`. `AdvertisementSpec` includes `service_type`, `port`, and `txt_records`. Both are appropriate.\n**Status:** Compliant\n\n---\n\n### [MAJOR] TXT Record Encoding Uses Hex Instead of Base64url\n**Spec reference:** Plan, Discovery Contract (`rk=<routing_key_base64url>`)\n**Finding:** The plan specifies `rk=<routing_key_base64url>`, but the implementation in `txt.rs` uses `hex::encode(routing_key)` / `hex::decode(rk_str)`. The `Cargo.toml` depends on `hex`, not `base64`. A 16-byte routing key encoded as hex is 32 characters; base64url would be 22 characters (unpadded). This is a concrete wire-format deviation from the plan.\n**Status:** Deviation\n\n---\n\n### [MAJOR] TXT Record Missing `relay` and `identity` Fields\n**Spec reference:** Plan, Discovery Contract (`relay=1`, `identity=1`)\n**Finding:** The plan specifies four TXT keys: `v=1`, `rk=<routing_key_base64url>`, `relay=1`, `identity=1`. The `encode_txt()` function only emits `v`, `rk`, and `port`. There is no support for `relay` or `identity` fields. The `decode_txt()` function similarly only parses those three fields.\n\nNote: `relay=1` is primarily a v0.6 feature (relay advertisement), so its absence in v0.4 Chunk 1 may be intentional. However, `identity=1` is described as a v0.4 signal indicating `/api/v1/identity` availability and its omission means the discovery controller cannot determine whether identity verification is possible before probing.\n**Status:** Deviation\n\n---\n\n### [MAJOR] TXT Record Contains `port` Field Not in the Discovery Contract\n**Spec reference:** Plan, Discovery Contract\n**Finding:** The plan's Discovery Contract lists `v`, `rk`, `relay`, and `identity` as TXT keys. The implementation adds a `port` field not present in the contract. The ROADMAP.md v0.4 section mentions `port=<http_port>` in the older TXT description, but the detailed plan (which supersedes the roadmap) does not include `port` because the SRV record already carries the port. The code includes comments acknowledging the SRV record is authoritative, treating TXT `port` as redundant.\n**Status:** Deviation (minor -- the redundant field does not cause harm, but deviates from the contract)\n\n---\n\n### [MAJOR] Unknown TXT Version Handling Does Not Match Spec\n**Spec reference:** Plan, Discovery Contract (\"Unknown version handling: log warning, skip peer, no crash\"); Chunk 1 item 5\n**Finding:** When `decode_txt()` encounters `v=2`, it returns `Err(TxtError::InvalidVersion(\"2\"))`. This does not crash, which is correct. However, the spec says to \"log a warning\" -- the current implementation delegates logging to callers (since `decode_txt` is a pure function). More importantly, the version check `if version != 1` treats any non-1 version as invalid. The function signature `Result<(RoutingKey, u16, u8), TxtError>` means callers can pattern-match on the error and skip the peer gracefully.\n\nThe behavior is functionally correct (skip peer, no crash), but the \"log warning\" part is caller responsibility. There is no test specifically verifying that `v=2` results in `InvalidVersion` (the existing `invalid_version` test uses `\"not_a_number\"`, and `version_256_overflows_u8` tests overflow, but `v=2` as a valid-but-unsupported version is not explicitly tested).\n**Status:** Partial -- functionally safe but missing an explicit `v=2` test case\n\n---\n\n### [INFO] Fake Backend for Deterministic Tests\n**Spec reference:** Plan, Chunk 1 item 6\n**Finding:** `FakeDiscoveryBackend` in `fake.rs` supports `inject_peer()`, `inject_updated()`, `inject_lost()`, implements `DiscoveryBackend`, and is gated behind `#[cfg(any(test, feature = \"test-utils\"))]`. The `test-utils` feature enables external crates to use it. Well-tested with 6 unit tests covering inject/receive, advertising state machine, multiple subscribers, and shutdown.\n**Status:** Compliant\n\n---\n\n### [INFO] mdns-sd as Optional Feature-Gated Backend\n**Spec reference:** Plan, Chunk 1 item 7\n**Finding:** The `mdns-sd` feature in `Cargo.toml` gates `dep:mdns-sd` and `dep:hostname`. The `MdnsSdBackend` module is conditionally compiled with `#[cfg(feature = \"mdns-sd\")]`. The backend uses `mdns_sd::ServiceDaemon` and correctly maps between `mdns_sd::ServiceEvent` variants and `DiscoveryEvent`.\n**Status:** Compliant\n\n---\n\n### [MINOR] bind_interfaces Not Supported\n**Spec reference:** Plan, Chunk 1 item 7 (\"DiscoveryBackend must accept interface filter from config (bind_interfaces)\")\n**Finding:** `MdnsSdBackend::new()` takes no parameters. There is no `bind_interfaces` configuration passed to the constructor or to `mdns_sd::ServiceDaemon`. The `mdns-sd` crate does support interface binding via `ServiceDaemon::new_with_if_addrs()` or similar API, but this is not wired up. The plan explicitly requires `bind_interfaces` support in Chunk 1.\n**Status:** Deviation\n\n---\n\n### [INFO] Service Type Matches Whitepaper\n**Spec reference:** WHITEPAPER.md Section 11.2, 11.6; ROADMAP.md v0.4\n**Finding:** `DEFAULT_SERVICE_TYPE` is `\"_reme._tcp.local.\"` which matches the whitepaper's `_reme._tcp.local` service type. The trailing dot is correct DNS-SD convention.\n**Status:** Compliant\n\n---\n\n### [MINOR] DiscoveryService Type Not Present\n**Spec reference:** Plan, \"Public Interfaces and Config Changes\" bullet (\"DiscoveryService\")\n**Finding:** The plan lists `DiscoveryService` as one of the types in `crates/reme-discovery`. No such type exists in the crate. The `DiscoveryBackend` trait and the concrete backends (`FakeDiscoveryBackend`, `MdnsSdBackend`) serve this role directly. The plan may have envisioned a wrapper/coordinator type that was deemed unnecessary during implementation.\n**Status:** Deviation (minor -- the functionality is covered by the trait + backends directly)\n\n---\n\n### [MINOR] ROADMAP.md TXT Record Key Name Mismatch\n**Spec reference:** ROADMAP.md v0.4 section\n**Finding:** The ROADMAP says TXT records use `id=<routing_key>`, but the plan says `rk=<routing_key_base64url>`, and the implementation uses `rk=<routing_key_hex>`. The implementation aligns with the plan's key name (`rk`) rather than the roadmap's (`id`). The plan is the more detailed and recent spec, so the implementation is correct to follow it.\n**Status:** Compliant (plan supersedes roadmap)\n\n---\n\n### [INFO] MdnsSdBackend Browse Thread Architecture\n**Spec reference:** N/A (implementation quality)\n**Finding:** The mDNS backend uses a separate OS thread (`std::thread::spawn`) to bridge the blocking `mdns-sd` receiver into the async broadcast channel. This is appropriate since `mdns_sd`'s `ServiceEvent` receiver is a std `mpsc::Receiver`. The `known` set correctly tracks instance names to differentiate `PeerDiscovered` vs `PeerUpdated` events. The browsing starts lazily on first `subscribe()` call.\n**Status:** Compliant\n\n---\n\n## Summary\n\n| Severity | Count | Details |\n|----------|-------|---------|\n| CRITICAL | 0 | -- |\n| MAJOR | 4 | Hex vs base64url encoding; missing `relay`/`identity` TXT fields; extra `port` TXT field; unknown version test gap |\n| MINOR | 3 | No `bind_interfaces` support; no `DiscoveryService` type; missing explicit `v=2` test |\n| INFO | 7 | All positive compliance findings |\n\n**Key deviations from plan:**\n\n1. **Hex encoding** for routing key instead of base64url -- a wire-format decision that should be reconciled with the plan before other consumers depend on it.\n2. **Missing `relay` and `identity` TXT fields** -- `relay` is arguably v0.6 scope, but `identity` is needed for v0.4 discovery controller logic.\n3. **Extra `port` TXT field** -- harmless but not in the discovery contract.\n4. **No `bind_interfaces` parameter** on `MdnsSdBackend` -- the plan explicitly requires this in Chunk 1.\n\nAll Chunk 1 structural items (trait, events, types, fake backend, feature-gated real backend) are delivered. The dependency constraint (no reme-transport/reme-identity) is fully respected.</result>\n<usage><total_tokens>63970</total_tokens><tool_uses>12</tool_uses><duration_ms>81236</duration_ms></usage>\n</task-notification>\nFull transcript available at: /tmp/claude-1000/-home-leon0399-Projects-reme/36b495c0-95b9-49fc-8523-b911e74011a9/tasks/ae4e851575d868134.output",
