`, `remove_http_target()`, `update_http_target(id, url)`\"\n**Finding:** The coordinator implements `add_http_target()`, `remove_http_target()`, and `replace_http_target(old_id, new_target: HttpTarget)` at `coordinator.rs:178-205`. The plan specifies `update_http_target(id, url)` which takes a URL; the implementation takes a full `HttpTarget` object and has different semantics (atomic remove+add under single lock, upsert behavior). The naming changed from `update_` to `replace_`.\n\nThis is arguably a better API (atomic swap prevents races where neither old nor new target exists), but it is a deviation from the plan's interface spec.\n**Status:** Deviation -- different name and signature, but improved semantics.\n\n---\n\n### [HIGH] `TransportRegistry` NOT converted to read-only view\n**Spec reference:** Plan, Chunk 2: \"Convert `TransportRegistry` to a read-only view: Remove `add_http_target()` and other mutation methods.\"\n**Finding:** `TransportRegistry` at `registry.rs` still has `pub async fn add_http_target()` and retains `with_composite()`. The plan requires removing mutation methods and replacing `with_composite()` with `with_coordinator()`. Neither change has been made.\n\nThis means there are two write authorities for target management: the coordinator's mutation API and the registry's own `add_http_target()`. This is the \"dual-authority problem\" (ARCH-6) that the plan was explicitly designed to eliminate.\n**Status:** Deviation -- registry still has mutation methods, violating single-write-authority invariant.\n\n---\n\n### [HIGH] `MessageReceiver` NOT deprecated\n**Spec reference:** Plan, Chunk 2: \"Deprecate `MessageReceiver` -- superseded by `TransportCoordinator::subscribe()`\"\n**Finding:** `MessageReceiver` at `receiver.rs` is still fully present, exported from `lib.rs:44` as a public type, and has no `#[deprecated]` attribute. The plan requires deprecation (and removal if no other consumers exist).\n\n`lib.rs:44`: `pub use receiver::{MessageRece