ig struct. Without periodic refresh, a DHCP reassignment that does not trigger an mDNS update will leave a stale target in the coordinator indefinitely, potentially routing messages to the wrong device.\n**Status:** Deviation\n\n### [MAJOR] No stale-peer lifecycle (Suspended state, circuit breaker, stale_timeout)\n**Spec reference:** Plan, Stale-Peer Lifecycle -- \"Mark target as Suspended\"; \"Circuit breaker (2 failures for Ephemeral)\"; \"stale_timeout (60s) proactive re-verification\"\n**Finding:** None of the three stale-peer mechanisms exist. There is no `Suspended` state, no failure counter, no `stale_timeout`. Peers go directly from verified to removed only via `PeerLost` mDNS events. If a peer becomes unreachable without sending an mDNS goodbye (e.g., abrupt power loss), its target remains registered and the coordinator will keep attempting delivery with no circuit breaker.\n**Status:** Deviation\n\n### [MAJOR] No channel binding in identity verification (SEC-3)\n**Spec reference:** Plan, Identity Verification Flow -- \"Channel binding (SEC-3 mitigation): The signed data becomes: `reme-identity-v1:` || challenge || responder_ip:port || node_pubkey\"\n**Finding:** `build_identity_sign_data()` in `crates/reme-encryption/src/lib.rs:376` signs only `\"reme-identity-v1:\" || challenge || node_pubkey` (81 bytes). The responder IP:port is not included. The controller's `verify_peer_identity()` does not pass the address to the sign-data builder. This leaves the MITM relay attack vector open: an attacker can forward the challenge to the real peer, receive a valid signature, and relay it back to the verifier. The plan explicitly created Chunk 5 for this, noting it \"can overlap with Chunk 4\", so this is an expected deferral, but the code has no TODO or tracking reference.\n**Status:** Deviation (expected -- Chunk 5 not yet implemented, but no tracking comment in the verification code)\n\n### [MINOR] Timing safety: short-circuits on first candidate match (SEC-2)\n**Spec reference:** Plan, Identity Verification Flow -- \"always iterate all N and use constant-time comparison for the final pass/fail decision. Do not short-circuit on first match.\"\n**Finding:** In `verify_peer_identity()` at line 364, the loop over candidates breaks on the first successful `verify_xeddsa()` call (line 365 returns `Ok(Some(...))`). The plan says to iterate all N candidates and use a constant-time final decision to prevent timing side-channel leakage of which candidate index matched. The current implementation leaks timing information proportional to the position of the matching candidate in the list.\n**Status:** Deviation\n\n### [MINOR] Config field name mismatch: `auto_direct_known_contacts` vs `allow_direct_lan`\n**Spec reference:** Plan, Public Interfaces and Config Changes -- `lan_discovery.auto_direct_known_contacts` default `true`\n**Finding:** The plan specifies `auto_direct_known_contacts`. The implementation uses `allow_direct_lan`. The semantic meaning is similar but the names differ. Additionally, the plan specifies `refresh_interval_secs` (default 300) which is completely absent from the config struct.\n**Status:** Partial (field exists with different name; `refresh_interval_secs` missing entirely)\n\n### [COMPLIANT] Subscribes to DiscoveryEvent stream\n**Spec reference:** Plan, Chunk 3\n**Finding:** The `spawn()` function takes a `broadcast::Receiver<DiscoveryEvent>` and loops on `events.recv()`, handling `PeerDiscovered`, `PeerUpdated`, and `PeerLost`. Handles `Lagged` and `Closed` errors.\n**Status:** Compliant\n\n### [COMPLIANT] Matches candidates against known contacts using advertised rk\n**Spec reference:** Plan, Chunk 3\n**Finding:** `contact_index: HashMap<[u8; 16], Vec<PublicID>>` is built from contacts at construction. `handle_discovered()` decodes TXT records to extract `routing_key`, then looks up candidates via `self.contact_index.get(&routing_key)`.\n**Status:** Compliant\n\n### [COMPLIANT] Skips HTTP probe when rk match