and::random()`). Response is deserialized as `IdentityResponse { signature }`. Signature is verified via `candidate.verify_xeddsa(&sign_data, &signature)`. The protocol matches the whitepaper's description. The whitepaper says the response includes `node_pubkey, routing_keys, signature`, but the actual `IdentityResponse` only deserializes `signature`. This is acceptable because the candidates are already known from the `contact_index`; the node_pubkey is implicit.\n**Status:** Compliant\n\n### [INFO] Response size guard uses post-download check\n**Spec reference:** N/A (defense-in-depth observation)\n**Finding:** `MAX_IDENTITY_RESPONSE_BYTES` (4096) is checked after `resp.bytes().await?` completes. The `reqwest::Client` has a 5-second timeout which bounds total download time, but a malicious peer could stream up to the timeout before the size check triggers. The code comment at line 343 acknowledges this design (\"content_length() relies on the Content-Length header which a malicious peer can omit\"). This is acceptable given the timeout, but `response.content_length()` could be used as an early-exit optimization before reading the body.\n**Status:** Compliant (acceptable trade-off)\n\n### [INFO] No `routing_keys` field in identity response\n**Spec reference:** WHITEPAPER 11.6 -- \"Response includes node_pubkey, routing_keys, signature\"\n**Finding:** `IdentityResponse` only has `signature`. The whitepaper says the response should include `node_pubkey` and `routing_keys`. The controller works around this by testing the signature against all candidates from the contact index. This is functionally equivalent and arguably better (the peer cannot lie about which pubkey it holds -- the signature proves it). However, it deviates from the whitepaper's described response format.\n**Status:** Deviation (functionally equivalent, whitepaper may need updating rather than the code)\n\n---\n\n## Summary\n\n| Severity | Count | Key items |\n|----------|-------|-----------|\n| MAJOR | 4 | Missing `verified_peer_index`, no periodic refresh, no stale-peer lifecycle, no channel binding |\n| MINOR | 2 | Timing side-channel on candidate iteration, config field name mismatch |\n| COMPLIANT | 7 | Event subscription, rk matching, HTTP skip, target add/remove, resource limits, enabled default, challenge-response |\n| INFO | 2 | Post-download size check, identity response format |\n\nThe most impactful gaps are the missing periodic refresh and stale-peer lifecycle. Without these, the controller cannot detect DHCP reassignment or clean up peers that disappear without mDNS goodbye packets, which directly undermines the WHITEPAPER 11.6 requirement for \"stale identities removed from Direct tier automatically.\" Channel binding (SEC-3) is a known deferral (Chunk 5). The timing side-channel (SEC-2) is a straightforward fix -- accumulate the match result across all candidates without early return.</result>\n<usage><total_tokens>71239</total_tokens><tool_uses>13</tool_uses><duration_ms>97265</duration_ms></usage>\n</task-notification>\nFull transcript available at: /tmp/claude-1000/-home-leon0399-Projects-reme/36b495c0-95b9-49fc-8523-b911e74011a9/tasks/aaeb9183fb7abe5e6.output",
