x exists to handle exactly that case.\n\n**Suggestion:** Always iterate all candidates, then return the first match found:\n```rust\nlet mut matched: Option<PublicID> = None;\nfor candidate in candidates {\n    let sign_data = build_identity_sign_data(&challenge, &candidate.to_bytes());\n    if candidate.verify_xeddsa(&sign_data, &signature) && matched.is_none() {\n        matched = Some(*candidate);\n        // do NOT break — continue iterating all N\n    }\n}\nOk(matched)\n```\nNote that `verify_xeddsa` itself must also not leak timing, which depends on the `xed25519` crate internals — worth verifying that `xed25519::PublicKey::verify` is constant-time.\n\n**Confidence: 90** — Directly contradicts the SEC-2 requirement stated in the plan.\n\n---\n\n### [CRITICAL] Identity challenge does not bind to the responder's IP:port (SEC-3 missing)\n\n**File:** `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/apps/client/src/discovery/controller.rs:324–369`\n\n**Description:** `build_identity_sign_data` produces `\"reme-identity-v1:\" || challenge || node_pubkey`. The responder's IP:port is not included in the signed data. A MITM on the LAN can intercept the challenge, forward it to the real peer, receive the valid signature, and relay it back — the verifier has no way to distinguish this from a direct response.\n\nThe plan explicitly mandates Chunk 5 (channel binding): \"The challenge must include binding material to prevent MITM relay attacks. The signed data becomes: `\"reme-identity-v1:\" || challenge || responder_ip:port || node_pubkey`.\"\n\nThis is acknowledged as a deferred chunk (\"Chunk 5: can overlap with Chunk 4\") not yet implemented, but it represents a fundamental gap in the security model as shipped. The controller currently constructs URLs like `format!(\"http://{}\", SocketAddr::new(addr, peer.port))` — the `addr` and `peer.port` are already available at call time and could be threaded into `verify_peer_identity`.\n\n**Suggestion:** Either: (a) block merging until Chunk 5 is implemented, or (b) add a prominent `// SEC-3: channel binding not yet implemented` comment on the `verify_peer_identity` function and a `FIXME` referencing the plan, so it can't be accidentally treated as complete. This is a known deferred item per the plan; flag it prominently rather than leaving it silent.\n\n**Confidence: 85** — Acknowledged in the plan as a pending security requirement; omission is intentional but undocumented at the call site.\n\n---\n\n### [MAJOR] `TargetId` in `handle_new` is constructed independently from the `HttpTarget`'s internal ID\n\n**File:** `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/apps/client/src/discovery/controller.rs:240–260`\n\n**Description:** In `handle_new`, the `target_id` stored in `PeerEntry` is constructed with `TargetId::http(url)` at line 240, *before* `coordinator.add_http_target(target)` at line 245. The `HttpTarget` itself also derives its `TargetId` internally via `HttpTargetConfig::new()` → `TargetId::http(&url)` (see `http_target.rs:49`). These happen to agree for plain HTTP URLs, but there is no assertion or API contract making this guaranteed.\n\nMore concretely: if `url` ever contains embedded auth credentials (`http://user:pass@host/`), `TargetId::http` sanitizes them away. The controller constructs its discovery URLs from `SocketAddr` (no credentials), so the paths agree today. But the independence is a latent coupling bug — if URL construction changes in either place, `handle_lost`/`handle_update` will silently fail to find the target in the coordinator pool because the `TargetId` used for removal no longer matches.\n\n**Suggestion:** Expose `target.id()` from `HttpTarget` (or derive it from `HttpTargetConfig` before constructing the target) so the stored `target_id` comes from the same source as the registered target, not from a separate `TargetId::http(url)` call. Alternatively, have `coordinator.add_http_target()` return the assigned `TargetId`.\n\n**Confidence: 80** — Today the two calls agree; the risk is forward fragility rather than a current breakage.\n\n---\n\n### [MAJOR] URL-unchanged short-circuit skips re-verification when identity may have changed\n\n**File:** `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/apps/client/src/discovery/controller.rs:157–169`\n\n**Description:** On a `PeerUpdated` event, if the current URL still appears in the updated peer's address list, verification is skipped entirely:\n\n```rust\nif stored_url_still_valid {\n    debug!(\"Update with matching address, skipping re-verification\");\n    return;\n}\n```\n\nThis is a security trade-off: it avoids redundant verification for benign address-unchanged updates, but it means a peer whose cryptographic identity has changed (key rotation, compromise) will retain its registered target as long as its IP doesn't move. The plan notes \"verified peers are refreshed periodically\" but that refresh mechanism is not implemented in this controller — there is no `refresh_interval_secs` timer, no stale-timeout, and no circuit-breaker hook. The short-circuit is therefore permanent for stationary peers, not temporary between periodic re-checks.\n\nThe plan states: \"On verification failure, mark target `Suspended` before removal. Circuit breaker provides fast path (2 failures for Ephemeral). `stale_timeout` (60s) triggers proactive re-verification.\" None of this exists yet, so the short-circuit has no safety net.\n\n**Suggestion:** Either: (a) document clearly that the short-circuit is intentional and that periodic re-verification (deferred) is the safety net — with a `FIXME` noting the missing refresh mechanism — or (b) remove the short-circuit for now since the refresh loop doesn't exist yet. A silent skip is harder to audit than an explicit TODO.\n\n**Confidence: 80** — The short-circuit is architecturally incomplete given the missing refresh mechanism.\n\n---\n\n### [MAJOR] `max_peers` clamped to minimum 1 silently, with no user warning\n\n**File:** `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/apps/client/src/discovery/controller.rs:94`